quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Using the @font-face Rule[/h1]

Each form of the font family must be declared using the [b]@font-face[/b] rule. In the example below, a custom font called "Delicious" is loaded and used for the heading.

[b]The HTML [/b][code format="html" ]<h1>This is Our Headline</h1>[/code]
[b]The CSS[/b][code format="css" codeId="598"]@font-face {
  font-family: Delicious; 
  src: url('Delicious-Roman.otf'); 
} 
@font-face { 
  font-family: Delicious; 
  font-weight: bold; 
  src: url('Delicious-Bold.otf'); 
}
h1{
   font-family: Delicious, sans-serif; 
}[/code]
Internet Explorer has a built-in bug when multiple @font-face rules are defined. Using [b]#iefix[/b] as shown below fixes the problem:[b][/b][code format="css" ]@font-face { 
   font-family: Delicious; 
   src: url('Delicious-Roman.ttf');
   src: url('Delicious-Roman.eot[b]?#iefix[/b]'); 
}[/code]
[b]Result: [/b][img id="2686" width="100%"]
[note]The question mark fools IE into thinking the rest of the string is a query string and loads just the EOT file. The other browsers follow the spec and select the format they need, based on the src cascade.[/note]
